Feasibility Conclusion from First Principles
FAST landing followed by Prufrock trench excavation, inflatable-bag tipping, and 5 m regolith burial represents the fastest, lowest-mass, most scalable pathway to permanent lunar habitats using the full SpaceX technology stack. Physics aligns optimally: 0.16 g reduces every force and energy demand; ubiquitous regolith supplies free, high-performance shielding, thermal inertia, and backfill; Starship’s pressure vessel arrives ready-qualified; FAST preserves the landing site; Prufrock delivers precise, automated geometry; and Dragon-derived bags enable gentle, controlled rotation without heavy machinery. Early uncrewed missions validate the robotic end-to-end workflow on the lunar surface. Crewed flights arrive to ready, radiation-protected, thermally stable volume numbering in the thousands of cubic meters. Each subsequent landing expands the base, bootstrapping ISRU for propellant and life support while building toward self-sustaining operations. This approach accelerates humanity’s off-Earth presence by turning expendable Starships into foundational infrastructure from the very first landings—leveraging rapid iteration, vertical integration, and first-principles engineering to establish a permanent SpaceX foothold on the Moon within initial mission cycles.
